treated with corticosteroids without improvement. Subsequently, he was treated successfully with other medications. However, he experienced a worsening of symptoms one week later, requiring mechanical ventilation.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Guillain-Barr\u00e9 syndrome","Multiple sclerosis","Myasthenia gravis","Chronic inflammatory demyelinating polyneuropathy","Amyotrophic lateral sclerosis"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s presentation is consistent with \u003Cstrong\u003EGuillain-Barr\u00e9 syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E, an acute inflammatory demyelinating polyneuropathy often triggered by infections such as cytomegalovirus. The rapid progression of ascending weakness, facial involvement, and autonomic instability, along with the need for mechanical ventilation, are characteristic of this condition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMultiple sclerosis\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with relapsing-remitting neurological symptoms, but it is less likely to cause such rapid progression and respiratory failure in the acute phase.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMyasthenia gravis\u003C/strong\u003E can cause fluctuating muscle weakness, but it is less commonly associated with preceding infections and does not typically present with sensory symptoms or autonomic instability.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChronic inflammatory demyelinating polyneuropathy\u003C/strong\u003E is a chronic condition with a slower progression compared to Guillain-Barr\u00e9 syndrome, making it less likely in this acute scenario.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAmyotrophic lateral sclerosis\u003C/strong\u003E is a progressive neurodegenerative disease that causes muscle weakness and atrophy, but it does not typically present with acute episodes or sensory symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Guillain-Barr\u00e9 syndrome is an acute inflammatory demyelinating polyneuropathy often triggered by infections.","It presents with rapidly progressive ascending weakness, areflexia, and can lead to respiratory failure requiring mechanical ventilation.","Corticosteroids are not effective in treating Guillain-Barr\u00e9 syndrome; intravenous immunoglobulin or plasmapheresis are the treatments of choice."],"references":["Pritchard J. Guillain-Barr\u00e9 syndrome. Clin Med (Lond). 2010 Aug;10(4):399-401. doi: 10.7861/clinmedicine.10-4-399. PMID: 20849020; PMCID: PMC4952175.","Leonhard SE, Mandarakas MR, Gondim FAA, Bateman K, Ferreira MLB, Cornblath DR, van Doorn PA, Dourado ME, Hughes RAC, Islam B, Kusunoki S, Pardo CA, Reisin R, Sejvar JJ, Shahrizaila N, Soares C, Umapathi T, Wang Y, Yiu EM, Willison HJ, Jacobs BC. Diagnosis and management of Guillain-Barr\u00e9 syndrome in ten steps. Nat Rev Neurol. 2019 Nov;15(11):671-683. doi: 10.1038/s41582-019-0250-9. Epub 2019 Sep 20. PMID: 31541214; PMCID: PMC6821638.","Bellanti R, Rinaldi S. Guillain-Barr\u00e9 syndrome: a comprehensive review. Eur J Neurol. 2024 Aug;31(8):e16365. doi: 10.1111/ene.16365. Epub 2024 May 30. PMID: 38813755; PMCID: PMC11235944."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60287"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17771"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60287","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60287"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-27T09:30:42+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-01T19:03:10+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10485"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74801"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":